Welcome to the Rumor Mill - where we imagine what Georgetown might be whispering about if Georgetown whispered about completely fictional things. Any resemblance to real persons or events is coincidental and honestly impressive.
💬 OVERHEARD AT OASIS A certain well-dressed gentleman was spotted at Oasis Cafe explaining to his lunch companion why the garbage situation is &ldquo;actually a strategic opportunity for community engagement.&rdquo;
His companion reportedly asked: &ldquo;So when the garbage getting picked up?&rdquo;
The gentleman&rsquo;s response: &ldquo;You&rsquo;re missing the bigger picture.&rdquo;
The garbage, we&rsquo;re told, is still there.
💬 THE ROUNDABOUT CHRONICLES Commuters stuck at Eccles Roundabout have reportedly started a WhatsApp group called &ldquo;Roundabout Therapy.&rdquo;
Activities include:
Sharing audiobook recommendations for the 45-minute wait Rating which lane moves fastest (spoiler: none of them) Debating whether to just swim across the river instead One member allegedly suggested they should hold their own parliament sessions during peak hours since &ldquo;we have more time than the National Assembly anyway.&rdquo;
💬 POLITICAL MUSICAL CHAIRS Word on the street is that certain opposition figures have been practicing their &ldquo;congratulations&rdquo; speeches - the kind you give when you don&rsquo;t mean it.
Meanwhile, other opposition figures have allegedly been practicing their &ldquo;I told you so&rdquo; speeches for approximately six months from now.
Everyone, it seems, is rehearsing for a play nobody has finished writing.
💬 THE SOLAR PANEL SITUATION A Linden businessman reportedly told his wife: &ldquo;We getting solar panels!&rdquo;
His wife: &ldquo;Good, we saving money!&rdquo;
Him: &ldquo;No, the government building them.&rdquo;
His wife: &ldquo;So we saving money?&rdquo;
Him: &ldquo;Eventually. Maybe. The meeting say so.&rdquo;
His wife: &ldquo;So I should still pay GPL this month?&rdquo;
Him: &ldquo;&hellip;yes.&rdquo;
💬 COURTHOUSE FASHION WATCH Legal observers have noticed an uptick in expensive suits at the Georgetown courthouse.
&ldquo;When the lawyers dress better than the judges,&rdquo; one observer noted, &ldquo;you know the case is either very important or very expensive. Usually both.&rdquo;
Coffee sales at nearby shops have reportedly tripled. Extended hearings are good for business.
💬 THE MASH PREPARATION DRAMA A Georgetown mas camp is allegedly in crisis mode after their lead designer announced the theme would be &ldquo;Sustainable Fashion&rdquo; - meaning recycled materials only.
Band members are reportedly concerned that &ldquo;recycled&rdquo; might mean &ldquo;those same feathers from 2019.&rdquo;
The designer insists it&rsquo;s &ldquo;innovation.&rdquo;
The band members insist it&rsquo;s &ldquo;budget cuts with extra steps.&rdquo;
💬 DIPLOMATIC DINNER DISASTER A certain embassy reportedly held a dinner last week where the main course arrived late because - you guessed it - the delivery truck got stuck in Eccles traffic.
By the time the food arrived, the appetizers had been so thoroughly consumed that one diplomat allegedly asked if &ldquo;the bread basket counts as the main course in Guyanese culture.&rdquo;
It does not. But everyone was too polite to say so.
💬 THE GYM CONFESSION Overheard at a Georgetown gym, 6 AM:
Person 1: &ldquo;You hear about the Police Academy thing?&rdquo;
Person 2: &ldquo;Yeah, serious allegations.&rdquo;
Person 1: &ldquo;At least they investigating.&rdquo;
Person 2: &ldquo;True. Pass the weights.&rdquo;
Person 1: &ldquo;You think they&rsquo;ll actually find anything?&rdquo;
Person 2: &ldquo;Brother, I just trying to do my biceps. Save the politics for after coffee.&rdquo;
💬 VENDOR WISDOM A Stabroek Market vendor, when asked about the Opposition Leader situation:
&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t follow politics. I follow money. When somebody come to my stall, I don&rsquo;t ask who they vote for. I ask what they buying.&rdquo;
Pause
&ldquo;But if you ask me personally? All ah dem need to sit down and talk. This country too small for all this drama.&rdquo;
She then sold three pounds of tomatoes and moved on with her day.
The Rumor Mill is entirely fictional and meant for entertainment. We make up everything. Don&rsquo;t sue us.
Disclaimer: All characters and situations in this column are entirely fictional. Any resemblance to actual persons, living or dead, or actual events is purely coincidental. This is satire, not reporting.

Your 5-minute Guyanese news circus — now with 100% less cash grants ☕🇬🇾
💸 CASH GRANTS: &ldquo;NOT SUSTAINABLE&rdquo; — PRESIDENT What Happened: President Ali declared that future cash grants are &ldquo;not sustainable,&rdquo; warning that &ldquo;some people would use this as a political opportunity.&rdquo;
The Backstory: Just one year ago, the government was &ldquo;committed to making future cash grants.&rdquo; What a difference 365 days makes!
The Math:
2025: &ldquo;We are committed to future cash grants!&rdquo; 2026: &ldquo;Cash grants are not sustainable.&rdquo; Also 2026: Oil production approaching 1 million barrels per day. Dem Boys Seh: &ldquo;When election coming, cash grant sustainable. When election done, cash grant unsustainable. Is like magic — de money just disappear!&rdquo;
🗑️ GEORGETOWN: MINISTER SAYS &ldquo;UNACCEPTABLE,&rdquo; CITY HALL SAYS &ldquo;WE&rsquo;LL GET BACK TO YOU&rdquo; What Happened: Local Government Minister Priya Manickchand held an emergency virtual meeting with Mayor Alfred Mentore over the &ldquo;unacceptable&rdquo; state of Georgetown. The city was given until 11 AM Monday to present a cleanup plan.
The Quote: &ldquo;Sanitation services, solid waste disposal, garbage collection etc must be reliable, predictable and effective. Or they are wasting time.&rdquo;
Translation: Georgetown smells like a combination of stagnant drain water, burning garbage, and broken promises.
Current Status of Georgetown:
☐ Clean ☐ Habitable ☑️ A talking point for politicians Dem Boys Seh: &ldquo;City Hall got till 11 AM to fix Georgetown. De garbage pile got till noon to laugh.&rdquo;
👩‍🏫 TEACHERS UNION: &ldquo;WE&rsquo;VE BEEN WRITING LETTERS, NOBODY ANSWERING&rdquo; What Happened: GTU President Coretta McDonald says the Education Ministry is delaying a crucial meeting on teacher promotions. Teachers haven&rsquo;t been promoted in three years, and many are retiring without the positions they deserved.
The Problem: The Teaching Service Commission was reconstituted without an Opposition Leader in place — which the GTU says is &ldquo;a direct ploy by the government.&rdquo;
Ministry&rsquo;s Apparent Strategy:
Receive letter requesting meeting Look at letter Put letter in drawer Repeat McDonald&rsquo;s Assessment: &ldquo;The longer the ministry delays the meeting with the GTU, our teachers are going to be in jeopardy again.&rdquo;
Dem Boys Seh: &ldquo;Teacher write letter to Ministry. Ministry write letter to TSC. TSC write letter to President. President write letter to 2027.&rdquo;
🏫 HINTERLAND SCHOOLS: &ldquo;FAR FROM OPERATIONAL READINESS&rdquo; — OPPOSITION What Happened: Opposition MP Sherod Duncan visited two school construction sites in Region Nine — the $215 million Nappi Secondary School and the $182 million Tabatinga Secondary School — and reported concerns about progress.
Duncan&rsquo;s Finding: The schools are &ldquo;far from operational readiness.&rdquo;
Government&rsquo;s Likely Response: &ldquo;The projects are 90% complete and on track for completion soon.&rdquo;
The Eternal Guyanese Infrastructure Formula:
Announced: 100% enthusiasm Groundbreaking: 100% ribbon Completion: 90% (forever) ⛽ GAS-TO-ENERGY: CONTROL ROOMS ARRIVE AT WALES What Happened: Control rooms for the Gas-to-Energy project were transported to the Wales site on Saturday evening, marking &ldquo;another key milestone.&rdquo;
Translation: Big boxes arrived. Milestone achieved.
Project Status Update:
✅ Boxes delivered ✅ Photos taken ✅ Press release issued ⏳ Actual gas flowing: End of 2026 (we think) Dem Boys Seh: &ldquo;Control room reach Wales. Now we just need de gas, de pipes, de turbines, de transmission lines, and de prayers.&rdquo;
🏥 HOSPITAL TRAGEDY: GPHC LAUNCHES INVESTIGATION What Happened: A 22-year-old pregnant woman died after jumping from the third-floor window of the female medical ward at Georgetown Public Hospital on Sunday evening. The hospital has launched an internal investigation.
The Questions: Family members are asking how a patient &ldquo;displaying clear psychological distress&rdquo; was able to leave her bed unaccompanied and access a window.
GPHC Statement: The hospital says a psychiatric evaluation was conducted and &ldquo;no psychotic symptoms or suicidal thoughts&rdquo; were identified.
If You Need Help: The Mental Health Unit&rsquo;s Suicide Prevention Hotline is 915. A mental health emergency is a real emergency.
🌊 NEW PASSENGER VESSEL: &ldquo;SOON TO BE RENAMED&rdquo; What Happened: A 2024-built vessel arrived from Greece to serve Region One (Barima-Waini). The ship sailed 5,200 nautical miles across the Atlantic.
Highlights:
Fully air-conditioned Brand new seating Will &ldquo;shorten travel time significantly&rdquo; The Real Question: What will they name it?
Our Suggestions:
MV Slow But Sure MV We Reach When We Reach MV Better Than The Last One MV Sea Minibus 🗳️ OPPOSITION LEADER: STILL LOADING&hellip; What Happened: Letters to the editor are now asking the Speaker of the National Assembly to explain why he hasn&rsquo;t convened the meeting to elect an Opposition Leader — over 3 months after elections.
Government&rsquo;s Position: &ldquo;We have no role in this.&rdquo;
Speaker&rsquo;s Position: [No comment available]
Constitutional Position: Article 184 says the Speaker must convene the meeting.
Actual Position: 🤷
Dem Boys Seh: &ldquo;Opposition Leader seat so empty, spider done build house inside.&rdquo;
📊 INFLATION: THE NUMBERS VS THE VIBES What Happened: A Stabroek News letter writer pointed out that official CPI data claims housing costs decreased by 1% since 2020.
The Official Numbers:
Housing: -1.0% Food: +50.7% Transportation: +3.3% The Reality: Try renting an apartment in Georgetown for 2020 prices. Go ahead. We&rsquo;ll wait.
Bonus: The New Guyana Marketing Corporation has stopped publishing market prices. No data, no problem!
Dem Boys Seh: &ldquo;According to government, everything cheap. According to market, everything expensive. According to we pocket, nothing deh inside.&rdquo;
🏏 SPORTS CORNER West Indies will warm up for the T20 World Cup with a three-match series against Afghanistan in Dubai. The World Cup starts February 7 in India and Sri Lanka.
Guyana Women&rsquo;s Cricket: Captain Shemaine Campbelle scored an unbeaten 50 as the defending champions beat Jamaica by 4 wickets in the CWI Women&rsquo;s Blaze T20 Championships.
☀️ WEATHER Georgetown: Partly cloudy with scattered showers of government announcements. High of 31°C. 90% chance of someone saying &ldquo;milestone.&rdquo;
🎯 FINAL SCORE Topic Government Says Reality Cash grants Not sustainable Oil revenue: very sustainable Georgetown Unacceptable Also unacceptable yesterday Teacher promotions We&rsquo;re working on it 3 years and counting Opposition Leader Not our problem Also not solved Inflation Under control Your grocery bill: LOL That&rsquo;s your Tuesday. Georgetown is dirty, teachers are waiting, cash grants are cancelled, and somewhere a control room is sitting in Wales wondering what it did to deserve this.
Read more at guyanadailybrief.com
Disclaimer: The Guyana Brief is satirical commentary. We read four newspapers so you don&rsquo;t have to. Any resemblance to actual competence is purely coincidental.

Speedeet and Wilar were supposed to be watching the Women&rsquo;s T20 match on TV. Guyana versus Jamaica, and Captain Campbelle was batting.
But then Speedeet&rsquo;s phone buzzed.
&ldquo;Nani need me go clinic with she,&rdquo; Speedeet said, reading the message. &ldquo;Blood pressure check.&rdquo;
Wilar shrugged. &ldquo;Match almost done anyway. We winning.&rdquo;
They found Nani at the bus stop, clutching her patient card — the worn folder that survived twenty years of clinic visits.
&ldquo;You boys coming? Good. Plenty confusion these days.&rdquo;
The polyclinic had TWO lines.
&ldquo;New system here! Old system there!&rdquo; the security guard shouted.
&ldquo;Register for what?&rdquo; Nani asked.
A woman turned around. &ldquo;Everything digital now. Computer system. But if you ain&rsquo;t register yet, you got to join the other line first.&rdquo;
Nani looked at her folder. &ldquo;I have this since 2006.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Don&rsquo;t matter. Everybody fresh.&rdquo;
Forty-five minutes later, they reached a desk with a brand-new laptop.
The young woman typed Nani&rsquo;s information, then opened the patient folder. She frowned at twenty years of handwritten notes, faded prescriptions, and coffee-stained test results.
&ldquo;I can only enter what I can read.&rdquo;
&ldquo;That say &lsquo;hypertension,&rsquo;&rdquo; Nani pointed. &ldquo;And that say &lsquo;reduce salt.&rsquo;&rdquo;
Fifteen minutes of squinting later: &ldquo;Okay, you&rsquo;re in the system. Take this number for the other line.&rdquo;
&ldquo;But I had 10 o&rsquo;clock appointment!&rdquo;
&ldquo;That was old system. Now you wait for the next available.&rdquo;
It was 11:30.
While Nani waited, the boys explored. Near the corner, an older man argued with a nurse.
&ldquo;What you mean you can&rsquo;t find my X-ray? I take it LAST MONTH!&rdquo;
&ldquo;Sir, it hasn&rsquo;t been migrated yet.&rdquo;
&ldquo;So I got to take ANOTHER one?&rdquo;
Speedeet whispered to Wilar: &ldquo;Progress messy, eh?&rdquo;
&ldquo;My father always say that.&rdquo;
At 1:15, Nani finally saw the doctor — a young woman staring at a computer screen.
&ldquo;Mrs. Persaud? Let me pull up your file&hellip;&rdquo;
Type. Click. Frown. Type again.
&ldquo;It says you registered today?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Today for COMPUTER. But I coming here since 2006.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Do you have documentation?&rdquo;
Nani held up her folder triumphantly. &ldquo;EVERYTHING in here.&rdquo;
They went through her handwritten records together. Blood pressure: 138 over 85. Slightly elevated but stable. Same medication continued.
&ldquo;I&rsquo;ll enter this in the new system for next time.&rdquo;
On the bus home, Nani tucked the folder back in her bag.
&ldquo;You keeping that?&rdquo; Speedeet asked.
&ldquo;Until computer prove it could remember good as paper, I keeping my backup.&rdquo;
Wilar was philosophical. &ldquo;System probably going be good. Eventually.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Eventually don&rsquo;t help Nani today,&rdquo; Speedeet said.
They passed construction on Main Street — another hotel going up.
&ldquo;Progress everywhere,&rdquo; Wilar observed.
&ldquo;Messy progress,&rdquo; Speedeet corrected.
Nani smiled. &ldquo;When I was girl, no clinic in the village. Had to travel hours. Now we complaining computer too slow.&rdquo; She paused. &ldquo;Different problems. Maybe better problems.&rdquo;
The bus rumbled on while Nani held her twenty years of history close, waiting for the future to catch up with the past.
Speedeet &amp; Wilar appears every Sunday.

A Weekly Profile of Guyanese Excellence
At Johns Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore, Dr. Sharmila Persaud is performing some of the world&rsquo;s most complex brain surgeries. But every morning, she looks at a photo on her desk: her grandmother&rsquo;s wooden house in Berbice, where she grew up without electricity.
The Journey &ldquo;People ask me how I got from there to here,&rdquo; Dr. Persaud says, gesturing around her state-of-the-art operating suite. &ldquo;I tell them: I got here because I started there.&rdquo;
Born in New Amsterdam in 1985, Sharmila was the first in her family to attend university. Her father drove a taxi. Her mother sold vegetables at the market. They had one dream: their daughter would become a doctor.
Against the Odds The path wasn&rsquo;t easy:
Studied by kerosene lamp when power was out (which was often) Walked 3 miles to school in Berbice rain Helped her mother at the market before classes Won a scholarship to Queen&rsquo;s College in Georgetown Graduated top of her class at University of Guyana medical school A scholarship to Johns Hopkins came next. Then residency. Then fellowship. Now, at 40, she&rsquo;s one of the leading neurosurgeons in North America.
The Guyana Connection But success hasn&rsquo;t severed her rootsâ€”it&rsquo;s strengthened them.
Dr. Persaud:
Returns to Guyana quarterly for medical missions Has trained 15 Guyanese doctors in neurosurgery techniques Established a scholarship fund for Berbice students Donated equipment to Georgetown Public Hospital Mentors young Guyanese doctors remotely &ldquo;I&rsquo;m successful because Guyana made me who I am,&rdquo; she explains. &ldquo;The work ethic, the resilience, the determinationâ€”that&rsquo;s all Guyana.&rdquo;
The Berbice Spirit She tells the story of performing a 14-hour surgery on a young patient last year. Exhausted, she almost asked her team to take over.
&ldquo;Then I remembered my mother standing in the market for 16 hours a day, never complaining. I thought: if she could do that selling vegetables, I can do this saving a life.&rdquo;
The surgery succeeded.
Advice for Young Guyanese Dr. Persaud is often asked to speak at schools in Guyana. Her message is consistent:
&ldquo;Your circumstances don&rsquo;t define your destination. I studied by lamplight. You have electricity and internet. You have no excuseâ€”and unlimited potential.&rdquo;
She pauses. &ldquo;But also: never forget where you came from. Success means nothing if you don&rsquo;t bring others along.&rdquo;
The Return Plan Dr. Persaud has a five-year plan: establish Guyana&rsquo;s first dedicated neurosurgery center in Georgetown.
&ldquo;We train excellent doctors in Guyana,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;But then we lose them because we don&rsquo;t have the facilities to use their skills. That has to change.&rdquo;
She&rsquo;s already raised $2 million toward the project. The Guyanese diaspora is contributing. So are international partners impressed by Guyana&rsquo;s potential.
&ldquo;My grandmother&rsquo;s generation left Guyana for opportunity,&rdquo; Dr. Persaud reflects. &ldquo;My generation left Guyana for education. The next generation? They should stay in Guyana for both.&rdquo;
Beyond Medicine Outside the hospital, Dr. Persaud maintains her Guyanese identity fiercely:
Cooks pepperpot for colleagues every Christmas Teaches her children Creolese phrases Wears her Guyana flag pin on her white coat Serves on the board of the Baltimore Guyanese Association &ldquo;I&rsquo;m Guyanese first,&rdquo; she says simply. &ldquo;Everything else is just what I do, not who I am.&rdquo;
The Photo That photo on her deskâ€”the one of her grandmother&rsquo;s house in Berbice?
&ldquo;It reminds me every day why I do this work,&rdquo; she explains. &ldquo;And reminds me that no matter how far I&rsquo;ve come, that&rsquo;s still home.&rdquo;
Dr. Sharmila Persaud proves what&rsquo;s possible when Guyanese excellence meets opportunity. And more importantly, she&rsquo;s ensuring the next generation won&rsquo;t have to leave Guyana to reach it.
Patriots&rsquo; Portfolio is a weekly feature celebrating successful Guyanese at home and abroadâ€”their journeys, their achievements, and their continued connection to the land that shaped them.

A Monthly Feature Celebrating Guyana&rsquo;s Progress
Walk down Main Street today, and you&rsquo;ll see something remarkable happening. Georgetown, once known for its colonial charm mixed with urban challenges, is undergoing a transformation that would have seemed impossible just five years ago.
The Numbers Tell the Story Since 2020, Georgetown has seen:
40+ new businesses opening on Main Street alone $500 million invested in waterfront development 300% increase in tourism infrastructure 12 new hotels under construction or recently opened Beyond the Statistics But the real story isn&rsquo;t in the numbers—it&rsquo;s in the people.
Rajiv Persaud, who returned from Toronto last year to open a tech startup, puts it simply: &ldquo;I left because I didn&rsquo;t see opportunity. I came back because now I see nothing but opportunity.&rdquo;
His company, GuyanaTech Solutions, now employs 45 Guyanese developers, many of whom were considering emigration before finding high-paying tech jobs at home.
The Waterfront Renaissance The Demerara River waterfront, once avoided after dark, now bustles with evening activity. New restaurants serve everything from traditional pepperpot to international fusion cuisine. Families stroll along newly lit promenades. Street vendors sell coconut water and plantain chips to office workers on lunch breaks.
&ldquo;My grandmother remembers when this was the heart of Georgetown,&rdquo; says Michelle Chen, owner of River&rsquo;s Edge Café. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re not building something new—we&rsquo;re reclaiming something we lost.&rdquo;
Challenges Remain Not everything is perfect. Traffic congestion has worsened with prosperity. Housing prices are rising faster than wages for some. The infrastructure upgrades can&rsquo;t keep pace with demand.
But these are, as Mayor Patricia Williams notes, &ldquo;the problems of a city that&rsquo;s growing, not dying.&rdquo;
The Diaspora Returns Perhaps most telling: the flow is reversing. More Guyanese are returning home than leaving. The &ldquo;brain drain&rdquo; that plagued the nation for decades is becoming a &ldquo;brain gain.&rdquo;
At the University of Guyana, Professor David Singh sees it in his classrooms: &ldquo;Students used to ask me how to get into foreign universities. Now they ask me how to build businesses here.&rdquo;
Looking Forward The transformation of Georgetown is just beginning. Plans are underway for:
A modern public transportation system Expansion of the Cheddi Jagan International Airport A new convention center to attract regional conferences Smart city initiatives including free public WiFi Green spaces and urban parks What It Means Georgetown&rsquo;s transformation is more than physical infrastructure. It represents a psychological shift—from a nation that exported its talent to one that nurtures and retains it.
Walking through Bourda Market on a Saturday morning, you hear it in conversations. Pride. Hope. Excitement about tomorrow.
One vendor, selling mangoes and plantains, summed it up: &ldquo;My children don&rsquo;t have to leave anymore. That&rsquo;s everything.&rdquo;
The Guyanese Horizon This monthly feature will chronicle Guyana&rsquo;s journey—the successes, the challenges, the people building tomorrow. Because understanding where we&rsquo;re going requires seeing where we are.
Georgetown is rising. And so is Guyana.
The Guyanese Horizon is a monthly feature celebrating progress, honoring heritage, and documenting the transformation of our nation.

Government Goes High-Tech! 📱 Ministry of Public Works proud to unveil their revolutionary new app: &ldquo;Report-A-Hole&rdquo;
Minister at launch ceremony: &ldquo;This app will TRANSFORM infrastructure management in Guyana!&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh, sitting front row, already downloading it before Minister finish talking.
Speedeet whisper: &ldquo;Bai, you even know how to use app?&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;How hard it could be? Is just button and camera!&rdquo;
Famous last words.
Monday Morning: De Beginning 6:00 AM - Uncle Ramesh Mission Starts
Uncle Ramesh wake up early, fully charge he phone, and decide to become Guyana&rsquo;s #1 pothole reporter.
&ldquo;If government want data, I go GIVE dem data!&rdquo;
He start driving from Buxton to Georgetown, eyes peeled.
6:15 AM - First Pothole
BOOM! Giant crater near Buxton market.
Uncle Ramesh pull over, open app:
Snap photo ✓ Add location ✓ Severity rating: 8/10 Description: &ldquo;Big hole, 2 feet wide, 6 inches deep&rdquo; SUBMIT ✓ App say: &ldquo;Thank you! Report #00001 received. Response time: 3-5 business days.&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh feel like Superman. &ldquo;I saving de nation, one pothole at a time!&rdquo;
8:30 AM - The Marathon Session
By time Uncle Ramesh reach Georgetown, he done report 47 potholes.
Each one with photo. Each one with GPS. Each one with detailed notes.
He phone battery: 23% He data plan: Crying He satisfaction level: Through de roof!
Speedeet call: &ldquo;Bai, where you dey? We was supposed to meet 7:30!&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;Sorry! I was busy doing CIVIC DUTY!&rdquo;
Tuesday: De Waiting Game Uncle Ramesh check app every hour.
All 47 reports showing: &ldquo;UNDER REVIEW 🔍&rdquo;
&ldquo;Good,&rdquo; he think. &ldquo;Government working hard!&rdquo;
He notice other people reporting too. App now showing 1,247 reports nationwide.
Uncle Ramesh to himself: &ldquo;Guyanese finally participating in democracy! Beautiful!&rdquo;
He report 23 MORE potholes just for good measure.
Wednesday: De Plot Thickens Uncle Ramesh now at 70 total reports.
Status still: &ldquo;UNDER REVIEW 🔍&rdquo;
But he notice something funny - that massive pothole near LBI? It got 15 DIFFERENT reports from 15 different people!
Same hole, 15 angles, 15 descriptions.
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;Everybody want credit for reporting de same hole! This is competitive civic duty!&rdquo; 😂
Thursday: DISASTER STRIKES! 6:00 AM
Uncle Ramesh open app.
Screen show: &ldquo;ERROR 503: Server Unavailable&rdquo;
He try again. Same thing.
He try 5 more times. STILL error.
Uncle Ramesh starting to panic. &ldquo;But&hellip; but&hellip; I had 3 new potholes to report!&rdquo;
2:00 PM - Government Statement
Ministry release message:
&ldquo;Report-A-Hole app experiencing technical difficulties due to OVERWHELMING response. We never anticipated THIS MANY potholes would be reported. Server capacity being upgraded. Back online soon.&rdquo;
Wilar: &ldquo;Dey never anticipated how many potholes Guyana have? Where dey been driving?&rdquo;
Speedeet: &ldquo;Probably helicopter.&rdquo; 😂
Friday: DE BIG REVEAL Morning - App Back Online!
Uncle Ramesh immediately check he 70 reports.
Status changed!
He eyes get BIG.
EVERY. SINGLE. REPORT. now showing: &ldquo;COMPLETED ✅&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh JUMP out he chair!
&ldquo;SEVENTY POTHOLES FIX IN ONE WEEK?! This is MIRACLE! This is RECORD! This is&hellip; this is&hellip; I gotta go see this!&rdquo;
He grab he keys, RUSH to he car, and start de Grand Inspection Tour.
De Grand Inspection Tour (AKA: De Disappointment) Pothole #1 (Buxton Market):
Uncle Ramesh park. Get out. Look at de road.
Pothole STILL DEY.
But now&hellip; it got a bright YELLOW CIRCLE paint around it.
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;Wha&hellip; what is THIS?!&rdquo;
Pothole #7 (Better Hope):
Still there. Yellow circle.
Pothole #15 (Enmore):
Still there. Yellow circle.
Uncle Ramesh starting to see a pattern.
Pothole #23 (Lusignan):
WAIT! This one ACTUALLY FILL! Real asphalt! Smooth road!
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;Okay, okay, we getting somewhere!&rdquo;
Potholes #24-46:
All still there. All with pretty yellow circles.
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;I living in a coloring book?!&rdquo;
Pothole #47 (Kitty Market):
Also ACTUALLY filled!
FINAL COUNT:
Potholes fixed: 2 Potholes painted: 68 Uncle Ramesh&rsquo;s faith in technology: Shaken Uncle Ramesh Calls Ministry He HAVE to understand this.
Ring ring
&ldquo;Ministry of Public Works, how can I help you?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Yes, I report 70 potholes, app say &lsquo;COMPLETED,&rsquo; but only 2 fix. De other 68 just have PAINT on dem!&rdquo;
&ldquo;Please hold, sir.&rdquo;
Hold music for 15 minutes - ironically, is Bob Marley &ldquo;Everything&rsquo;s Gonna Be Alright&rdquo;
Technical Support guy (Jason) come on:
&ldquo;Hello! You must be User #00001! Sir, you&rsquo;re FAMOUS here! Minister mentioned you in morning briefing!&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;That nice and all, but what about DE POTHOLES?!&rdquo;
Jason: &ldquo;Ah yes, let me explain. The yellow circles mean we VERIFIED the location. The pothole is now in our system for SCHEDULING.&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;So &lsquo;COMPLETED&rsquo; means y&rsquo;all COMPLETE de PAPERWORK?!&rdquo;
Jason: &ldquo;Well&hellip; the report PROCESSING is completed, yes. The actual REPAIR is a separate phase based on priority, budget, and resources.&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;So when de ACTUAL holes getting fix?&rdquo;
Jason: &ldquo;That depends on various factors, sir. But your reports are VERY helpful for our planning database!&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;Planning database?! I could PLANT CASSAVA in some of these holes!&rdquo;
Jason: &ldquo;I understand your frustration, sir. Would you like to speak with a supervisor?&rdquo;
Uncle Ramesh: &ldquo;Never mind. Thank you.&rdquo; Click
De App Store Reviews (Comedy Gold) By Friday evening, de review section is FIRE:
⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ Speedeet: &ldquo;Best comedy app of 2026! I laugh every time I open it! Forget Netflix!&rdquo;
⭐ Wilar: &ldquo;One star because I can&rsquo;t give ZERO. My car suspension file a formal complaint.&rdquo;
